# Atomic Commit Policy

Follow [`.conform.yaml`](.conform.yaml) for conventional commit shape
(types, scopes, header length, lower case, imperative, no trailing
period, DCO, GPG).

## One change per commit

- A commit describes **exactly one** change.
- The subject must **not** contain `and`. If you need `and`, split into
  two or more commits.
- Prefer a verb phrase that names one action (add X, fix Y, refactor Z).
- One mechanical action is one commit. Moving a constant, adding a
  factory, wiring a caller, and exporting a public name are separate
  commits even when they serve the same feature.

```text
# ❌ BAD — two changes in one subject
fix: correct exclude globs and update docs

# ✅ GOOD — split
fix: correct exclude globs
doc: document exclude glob behavior

# ❌ BAD — relocation mixed with new API work
wip: add export Config from public API
# (also moved DEFAULT_EXCLUDES and added from_mapping)

# ✅ GOOD — one action each
refactor: move default excludes to config module
refactor: construct run Config via from_mapping
wip: add export Config from public API
```

## Pipeline must pass

- Every commit must leave the tree in a state that passes the pipeline
  (tests, lint, and other CI checks this repo runs).
- Do not land a commit that only works when followed by another commit
  in the same push, except as noted for `wip` below.

## Types for preparatory and unfinished work

- Changes that only prepare the ground for a later changelog-worthy
  commit use type **`refactor`** (not the eventual loggable type).
- On **`dev/main`**, a change that *will* be changelog-worthy later is
  still committed as **`wip`**. Do **not** open a GitHub issue yet;
  promotion to master (cherry-pick or similar) may come later, when an
  issue can be created if instructed.
- Form the `wip` subject from the *eventual* conventional subject by
  dropping the colon after the future type and prefixing `wip:`:

```text
# eventual (on master, with issue)
add: export Config from public API

# on dev/main until then
wip: add export Config from public API
```

- `wip` commits may be amended or rebased later into the final typed
  message once ready for master.
- A new or updated case in **`tests/fix_test.py`** is a **fix**, not a
  refactor. On `dev/main` use `wip: fix …`, never `refactor: …`.

## Subject is the user-facing change

- The subject must read like a **changelog line for the end user** (or
  API consumer): what behavior is fixed, added, or changed.
- Do **not** name the implementation mechanism, helper, or library call
  in the subject. Those belong in the commit body if needed.
- Ask: “If this appeared in the release notes, would a user understand
  the benefit without reading the diff?” If not, rewrite.

```text
# ❌ BAD — implementation, not user value
refactor: clean docstrings with inspect cleandoc
fix: use cleandoc instead of splitlines

# ❌ BAD — too narrow / symptom-only without the product meaning
wip: fix false SIG503 on Returns header

# ✅ GOOD — user-facing behavior on dev/main
wip: fix evaluate docstring when description is missing
```

## Approve the message before committing

- Before `git commit`, show the exact subject (and body, if any) in
  chat and **wait for explicit approval** (e.g. “commit” or an edited
  message). Do not commit on the first draft without that go-ahead.

## Before committing

- Split the diff into atomic commits when the working tree mixes
  concerns.
- Choose type and scope from `.conform.yaml` (and `wip:` on `dev/main`
  when the change is eventually loggable).
- Write a subject without `and`, within the conform length limit, that
  passes the changelog test above.
- Get the user’s approval of the message, then commit.
